{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17564437","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17564437"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:14:31+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:14:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16980"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16980","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16980"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.94,0.01,0,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9670"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68117"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9670","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9670"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16980"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53574"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1094"},{"type":"tags","id":"1137"},{"type":"tags","id":"3288"},{"type":"tags","id":"3455"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22797"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35555"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48782"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68117","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/68117"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 52-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for review of recent investigation results. She has a three-month history of progressive dysphagia, weight loss of 8 kg, and occasional haematemesis. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. Two weeks ago, an endoscopy revealed a large oesophageal mass, and biopsies confirmed adenocarcinoma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears cachectic but otherwise well with vital signs within normal limits. When discussing the results, she states \u0027I\u0027m sure it\u0027s just acid reflux - the biopsy must be wrong. I feel fine now and I\u0027ve been eating better. I don\u0027t need to see an oncologist.\u0027\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following ego defence mechanisms best describes this patient\u0027s response?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Rationalisation","Denial","Reaction formation","Projection","Displacement"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case illustrates a classic example of \u003Cstrong\u003Edenial\u003C/strong\u003E as an ego defence mechanism. Despite clear evidence of oesophageal cancer from biopsy results, the patient refuses to accept the diagnosis, instead attributing her symptoms to a more benign condition. This represents an unconscious attempt to protect herself from the anxiety and distress associated with a cancer diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERationalisation\u003C/strong\u003E involves providing logical explanations for behaviours or situations to avoid acknowledging the true, more threatening cause. While the patient does attempt to explain away her symptoms, her complete rejection of the diagnosis goes beyond rationalisation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDisplacement\u003C/strong\u003E involves redirecting emotions, usually negative ones, from their original source to a less threatening target. There is no evidence of the patient transferring her feelings onto another person or object.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProjection\u003C/strong\u003E involves attributing one\u0027s own unacceptable thoughts, feelings, or impulses to another person or thing. The patient is not projecting her feelings onto others but rather refusing to acknowledge her diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReaction formation\u003C/strong\u003E involves converting an unacceptable feeling or impulse into its opposite. This would be more likely if the patient had become excessively concerned about her health rather than dismissing it.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding defence mechanisms is crucial in medical practice as they can significantly impact patient care and compliance with treatment. While denial can initially help patients cope with devastating news, persistent denial may require psychological support to help the patient accept their diagnosis and engage with necessary treatment.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Denial is a primitive defence mechanism where a person refuses to accept external reality because it is too threatening","Medical denial commonly presents as minimisation or rejection of serious diagnoses despite clear evidence","While denial can be maladaptive, it can also serve as a temporary coping mechanism allowing gradual adjustment to difficult news"],"references":["Sadock BJ, Sadock VA, Ruiz P. Kaplan and Sadock\u0027s comprehensive textbook of psychiatry. lippincott Williams \u0026 wilkins; 2017 May 11."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53574"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16980"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53574","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53574"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-09T10:11:25+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-09T10:12:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9670"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68117"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udfad","name":"Psychiatry","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updated